Topic 4: introduction to creating summary statistics and plots in R

This online learning material is part of a series on data science created for the Veterinary Online Collection. This topic is part 4 in the series, and aims to give an introduction to creating summary statistics and plots in the statistical programming language R. It is targeted primarily at veterinary undergraduate students, but anybody is welcome to use the material for other undergraduate and postgraduate courses as well as for self-directed study. It is assumed that you have already worked through parts 1-3 of this series on data science.

Summary statistics

There are a number of different ways to create summary statistics in R, including dedicated R packages such as the table1 package, but the most flexible method is to use the same tidyverse tools that we learned about in topic 3. Using a combination of group_by, summarise, pivot_wider and pivot_longer we can create anything we need, and then output the summary statistics back to an Excel file so that we can include them in a report or manuscript.

Let’s carry on where we left off with the lameness data; I’ll assume that you have completed the exercise for topic 3 and obtained the following data frame:

I’ll also assume that your working directory is set correctly, and that the tidyverse package is loaded, as described in previous topics.

Now let’s say we want to create a table showing some summary statistics stratified by herd and whether or not the animals were selected - for example the proportion of animals in each breed, mean daily milk yield and standard deviation in daily milk yield. We can achieve this by breaking the task down into several sub-tasks, and then joining the data frames at the end.

Summarising categorical variables

Creating summary statistics for categorical variables basically entails making counts of each observation, stratified by whatever columns we want to. Here we use breed distribution as an example. All we need to do is count the occurrences of breed along with the stratifying variables, then use complete and replace_na to fill in the implicit 0 numbers:

topic_3_solution |>
  count(Herd, Selected, BreedText) |>
  complete(Herd, Selected, BreedText) |>
  replace_na(list(n = 0)) ->
  table1_breed

This gives us counts in a new column n:

table1_breed
## # A tibble: 12 × 4
##    Herd   Selected BreedText     n
##    <chr>  <fct>    <chr>     <int>
##  1 Herd_A no       Holstein      0
##  2 Herd_A no       Jersey      430
##  3 Herd_A yes      Holstein      0
##  4 Herd_A yes      Jersey       50
##  5 Herd_B no       Holstein     85
##  6 Herd_B no       Jersey       25
##  7 Herd_B yes      Holstein     44
##  8 Herd_B yes      Jersey        6
##  9 Herd_C no       Holstein     33
## 10 Herd_C no       Jersey      127
## 11 Herd_C yes      Holstein      7
## 12 Herd_C yes      Jersey       43

Maybe it would be nice to add percentages in brackets. We can do this using group_by, mutate, str_c, and a couple of new functions sum and round, as follows:

table1_breed |>
  group_by(Herd, Selected) |>
  mutate(totaln = sum(n)) |>
  ungroup() |>
  mutate(percent = round(n / totaln * 100, digits = 0)) |>
  mutate(text = str_c(n, " (", percent, "%)")) ->
  table1_breed

The sum function does what you would expect (summing the counts given by n), but notice that we use group_by before mutate so that the sum (“totaln”) is stratified by Herd and Selected. This allows us to calculate a percentage of each breed within this stratification by dividing n by totaln and multiplying by 100. We use the round function to give the percentage to the nearest whole number. Then we have a slightly complicated looking str_c function call, but this is really quite simple if you break it down - all it does is to paste together the following:

  • n is the number of observations (created by count)
  • ” (” is just text, meaning to put in a space and then an open bracket after the count
  • percent is the (rounded) percentage that we just calculated
  • “%)” means to finish off with a percentage symbol and a close bracket

Notice that we re-use the data fame name table1_breed at the start and end of the pipe chain; this means we over-write the data frame with the new one with extra columns:

table1_breed
## # A tibble: 12 × 7
##    Herd   Selected BreedText     n totaln percent text      
##    <chr>  <fct>    <chr>     <int>  <int>   <dbl> <chr>     
##  1 Herd_A no       Holstein      0    430       0 0 (0%)    
##  2 Herd_A no       Jersey      430    430     100 430 (100%)
##  3 Herd_A yes      Holstein      0     50       0 0 (0%)    
##  4 Herd_A yes      Jersey       50     50     100 50 (100%) 
##  5 Herd_B no       Holstein     85    110      77 85 (77%)  
##  6 Herd_B no       Jersey       25    110      23 25 (23%)  
##  7 Herd_B yes      Holstein     44     50      88 44 (88%)  
##  8 Herd_B yes      Jersey        6     50      12 6 (12%)   
##  9 Herd_C no       Holstein     33    160      21 33 (21%)  
## 10 Herd_C no       Jersey      127    160      79 127 (79%) 
## 11 Herd_C yes      Holstein      7     50      14 7 (14%)   
## 12 Herd_C yes      Jersey       43     50      86 43 (86%)

The final step is to take the columns we need and make the data wide so that we have breeds in columns rather than rows:

table1_breed |>
  select(Herd, BreedText, Selected, text) |>
  pivot_wider(names_from = BreedText, values_from = text) ->
  table1_breed

And we have our final result:

table1_breed
## # A tibble: 6 × 4
##   Herd   Selected Holstein Jersey    
##   <chr>  <fct>    <chr>    <chr>     
## 1 Herd_A no       0 (0%)   430 (100%)
## 2 Herd_A yes      0 (0%)   50 (100%) 
## 3 Herd_B no       85 (77%) 25 (23%)  
## 4 Herd_B yes      44 (88%) 6 (12%)   
## 5 Herd_C no       33 (21%) 127 (79%) 
## 6 Herd_C yes      7 (14%)  43 (86%)

Summarising numeric variables

For numeric variables, we will typically want standard summary statistics in different columns. This could be any of the following:

  • mean - using the mean function
  • median - using the median function
  • min or max - which are also functions in R
  • variance - using the var function
  • standard deviation - either using the sd function, or by using the sqrt function on a variance
  • quantiles or quartiles - using the quantile function with probabilities given by the probs argument

In our case we only need mean and standard deviation of daily milk yield. To do this we first convert the yield per milking event into a daily yield by multiplying by the milking frequency, then use group_by and summarise to get the stratified summary statistics we need:

topic_3_solution |>
  mutate(DailyYield = MilkYield * MilkFreq) |>
  group_by(Herd, Selected) |>
  summarise(MilkMean = mean(DailyYield), MilkSD = sd(DailyYield), .groups="drop") ->
  table1_milk

This gives us the following data frame:

table1_milk
## # A tibble: 6 × 4
##   Herd   Selected MilkMean MilkSD
##   <chr>  <fct>       <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1 Herd_A no           25.7   6.06
## 2 Herd_A yes          24.9   5.80
## 3 Herd_B no           23.0   4.20
## 4 Herd_B yes          22.6   4.03
## 5 Herd_C no           23.7   6.75
## 6 Herd_C yes          24.8   6.77

However, these numbers are very precise, so we might want to round them for a publication output! We also need to make sure that we get a consistent number of decimal places, so for example if we round to 1 decimal place we want a yield of 23.042 to be shown as 23.0 and not 23. We do this using the round and format functions:

table1_milk |>
  mutate(MilkMean = format(round(MilkMean, digits = 1))) |>
  mutate(MilkSD = format(round(MilkSD, digits = 1))) ->
  table1_milk

table1_milk
## # A tibble: 6 × 4
##   Herd   Selected MilkMean MilkSD
##   <chr>  <fct>    <chr>    <chr> 
## 1 Herd_A no       25.7     6.1   
## 2 Herd_A yes      24.9     5.8   
## 3 Herd_B no       23.0     4.2   
## 4 Herd_B yes      22.6     4.0   
## 5 Herd_C no       23.7     6.8   
## 6 Herd_C yes      24.8     6.8

This looks much better.

Combining sub-tables

We can now combine our two sub-tables into the overall table we need by joining on the stratifying variables:

table1_breed |>
  left_join(
    table1_milk,
    by=c("Herd","Selected")
  ) ->
  table1

This gives us a publication-ready table:

table1
## # A tibble: 6 × 6
##   Herd   Selected Holstein Jersey     MilkMean MilkSD
##   <chr>  <fct>    <chr>    <chr>      <chr>    <chr> 
## 1 Herd_A no       0 (0%)   430 (100%) 25.7     6.1   
## 2 Herd_A yes      0 (0%)   50 (100%)  24.9     5.8   
## 3 Herd_B no       85 (77%) 25 (23%)   23.0     4.2   
## 4 Herd_B yes      44 (88%) 6 (12%)    22.6     4.0   
## 5 Herd_C no       33 (21%) 127 (79%)  23.7     6.8   
## 6 Herd_C yes      7 (14%)  43 (86%)   24.8     6.8

But what happens if one of our co-authors wants the table arranged differently, i.e. summary statistics in rows and stratifying variables in columns? Remember that we can use pivot_longer and pivot_wider to re-shape tables however we want! This is usually easiest by converting the table into long format:

table1 |>
  pivot_longer(cols = Holstein:MilkSD, names_to="Variable", values_to = "Statistic") ->
  table1_long

table1_long
## # A tibble: 24 × 4
##    Herd   Selected Variable Statistic 
##    <chr>  <fct>    <chr>    <chr>     
##  1 Herd_A no       Holstein 0 (0%)    
##  2 Herd_A no       Jersey   430 (100%)
##  3 Herd_A no       MilkMean 25.7      
##  4 Herd_A no       MilkSD   6.1       
##  5 Herd_A yes      Holstein 0 (0%)    
##  6 Herd_A yes      Jersey   50 (100%) 
##  7 Herd_A yes      MilkMean 24.9      
##  8 Herd_A yes      MilkSD   5.8       
##  9 Herd_B no       Holstein 85 (77%)  
## 10 Herd_B no       Jersey   25 (23%)  
## # … with 14 more rows

And then using this long format to pivot back into a different wide format to what we started with. Sometimes we need to create new columns to combine different stratifying variables:

table1_long |>
  mutate(Strata = case_when(
    Selected == "no" ~ str_c(Herd, " - not scored"),
    Selected == "yes" ~ str_c(Herd, " - selected for scoring"),
  )) |>
  select(Strata, Variable, Statistic) |>
  pivot_wider(names_from = Strata, values_from = Statistic)
## # A tibble: 4 × 7
##   Variable `Herd_A - not scored` Herd_A - sele…¹ Herd_…² Herd_…³ Herd_…⁴ Herd_…⁵
##   <chr>    <chr>                 <chr>           <chr>   <chr>   <chr>   <chr>  
## 1 Holstein 0 (0%)                0 (0%)          85 (77… 44 (88… 33 (21… 7 (14%)
## 2 Jersey   430 (100%)            50 (100%)       25 (23… 6 (12%) 127 (7… 43 (86…
## 3 MilkMean 25.7                  24.9            23.0    22.6    23.7    24.8   
## 4 MilkSD   6.1                   5.8             4.2     4.0     6.8     6.8    
## # … with abbreviated variable names ¹​`Herd_A - selected for scoring`,
## #   ²​`Herd_B - not scored`, ³​`Herd_B - selected for scoring`,
## #   ⁴​`Herd_C - not scored`, ⁵​`Herd_C - selected for scoring`

This method is so flexible that it allows you to achieve almost any table format you want to. The only thing you will need to do manually in Excel are to add formatting (e.g. bold) and tidy up column names (e.g. merging cells, splitting column names onto different rows).

Exporting tables and data from R

There are a number of situations where we might want to export a data frame from R, and a number of different formats that we can use to do this. For example:

  • Exporting a table for publication
  • Exporting a data set to Excel or CSV, perhaps for a collaborator that doesn’t use R
  • Exporting a data frame in a way that is easy to re-load into R, perhaps for a collaborator that doesn’t have the raw data

Exporting a table for publication

Let’s say that we want to copy-paste our table1 into a Word document containing a report or manuscript. We can’t copy the table directly from R very easily, so we need to go via an intermediate solution such as Excel. For this we will need to load the writexl package, and use the write_xlsx function:

library("writexl")
write_xlsx(table1, path="table1.xlsx")

You will now have an Excel file called “table1.xlsx” saved in the working directory, containing the table we created.

The write_xlsx function can also save a file with multiple sheets, for example:

write_xlsx(list(wide=table1, long=table1_long), path="table1.xlsx")

Notice that we are over-writing an existing file here - you should therefore be careful not to accidentally over-write a file that you have made changes in! Also note that the file cannot be open in another program (e.g. Excel) when it is being over-written; if you get an error when running this code then make sure Excel is not open and try again.

If you want to save time when opening the file, we can use the system function to automatically open the Excel file for us once it is created, like so:

system("open table1.xlsx")

Exporting data to Excel and CSV

Exporting a dataset to Excel is just like exporting a table to Excel, as shown above. If you are sending data to somebody then it would be a good idea to include description sheets. You can even create these as data frames directly in R using the tribble function and then save them using write_xlsx if you want to:

metadata <- tribble(
  ~Field, ~Value,
  "Dataset", "Processed data on lameness in cattle, version 1.0",
  "Date", "2023-02-27",
  "Description", "An example dataset of lameness observations in dairy cattle, processed to join with registry data on milk yield",
  "Name", "Matt Denwood",
  "Email", "...@...",
  "Source", "Lameness observations were collected on farm visits, other data was extracted from Danish registries before the vists. Note: this is actually simulated data!", 
  "Reference", "Carried out as part of my PhD on lameness in dairy cattle, funded by SEGES with grant number S6716245.  Note: supporting material for this training exercise can be found at https://www.costmodds.org/teaching/voc_data_science/topic1/"
)

Sometimes you might want to export data in a more generic format that other software is able to understand more easily. In this case, CSV (comma-separated values) is a good choice. For this we use the write_csv function:

write_csv(topic_3_solution, file="lameness_data.csv")

This creates a text file in CSV format with the data, that you can open in Excel or other statistical analysis software. However, if you have a computer in a Scandinavian locale then Excel won’t read the file properly because it is expecting a semi-colon separated file. In that case, you can try this code instead:

write_csv2(topic_3_solution, file="lameness_data.csv")

If you have used Scandinavian characters such as å ø or æ then these might not be displayed correctly in Excel. If that happens to you, try the write_excel_csv or write_excel_csv2 functions - these functions add a Byte order mark to the data to tell Excel that the file is UTF-8 encoded, so should resolve these problems.

Exporting data for later use in R

Exporting data to Excel or CSV format will remove some of the information on column formats, for example factors and sometimes dates will be turned into text. If we want to save data without losing this information, we can use the save function:

save(topic_3_solution, table1, file = "processed_lameness_data.rda")

This will save all of the variables and/or data frames we specify into the filename given by the file argument. We can then re-load the data using load:

(load("processed_lameness_data.rda"))
## [1] "topic_3_solution" "table1"

Putting the extra parentheses () around the load function causes the names of the stored variables / data frames to be shown in the console, which can be handy if we forgot the names of what we saved!

The advantages of this approach compared to Excel or CSV formats are (1) the file format is smaller and the data saves/loads faster (and can be made even smaller and faster using the qs package), and (2) the data is loaded in exactly the same format as it was saved. The only disadvantage is that the format is specific to R, i.e. it is NOT useful for sharing data with people that don’t use R!

Plots

There are a number of different plotting systems used in R, but by far the most flexible is the ggplot system provided by the ggplot2 package (which is part of tidyverse). A complete overview of ggplot is outside the scope of this topic, but the basic principles are as follows.

Generating plots

We always start with the ggplot function, which takes two arguments:

  1. The data frame we are working with - this should always be in long format for ggplot
  2. The aesthetics of the plot - i.e. which columns go on the x and y axes, what should be used to stratify by colour, etc

The aesthetics must be created using the aes function. For example:

ggplot(topic_3_solution, aes(x=DaysInMilk, y=MilkYield, col=Herd))

On its own this function only produces an empty plot: to do something interesting we need to add one or more layer. There are different types of plot layer depending on what we want to show with the plot, for example:

  • geom_point for a basic scatterplot (x/y plot)
  • geom_bar for a barchart
  • geom_boxplot for a box plot
  • geom_hist for a histogram
  • stat_smooth for a smoothed line of best fit
  • stat_ecdf for an empirical cumulative distribution function plot

There are many many other possibilities, but these cover the basics…

To add one or more layer we use the + symbol, and just like with pipe chains it is clearest to put each new layer on a new line:

ggplot(topic_3_solution, aes(x=DaysInMilk, y=MilkYield, col=Herd)) +
  geom_point() +
  stat_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

Here is an example of a boxplot:

ggplot(topic_3_solution, aes(x=Herd, y=MilkYield, fill=Breed)) +
  geom_boxplot()

This time we use fill rather than col, as we want a fill colour for the boxes rather than line/point colour.

Sometimes we need to do some pre-processing of a data frame to obtain the data we want to plot, for example:

  • Filter only strata that we want to plot
  • Filter out missing observations
  • Change the data from wide to long format
  • Summarise the data to counts by stratifying variables

For example:

topic_3_solution |>
  count(Herd, Breed) ->
  plotdata

ggplot(plotdata, aes(x=Herd, y=n, fill=Breed)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity")

Note that when providing geom_bar with counts as we have done here, we need to specify the stat=“identify” argument. We can also tweak the plot to flip the axes, and change the position to “dodge” (from the default “stack”) so that the bars are shown next to each other:

ggplot(plotdata, aes(x=Herd, y=n, fill=Breed)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", position="dodge") +
  coord_flip()

Notice that Herd C doesn’t have a row for Jersey cows, so the bar is expanded to cover both rows. If we wanted the bar width to be like the others, then we need to convert the implicit missing jerseys to an explicit zero count in the plot data:

topic_3_solution |>
  count(Herd, Breed) |>
  complete(Herd, Breed) |>
  replace_na(list(n=0)) ->
  plotdata

ggplot(plotdata, aes(x=Herd, y=n, fill=Breed)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", position="dodge") +
  coord_flip()

Saving plots

Once we have created a plot we like, we want to save it to a file for later use (e.g. inclusion in a report or manuscript). To do this, we first create a plot, then use the ggsave function with argument specifying the filename to use:

ggplot(plotdata, aes(x=Herd, y=n, fill=Breed)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", position="dodge") +
  coord_flip()

ggsave("figure1.pdf")
## Saving 7 x 5 in image

This creates a PDF containing our figure in the current working directory. Most of the time a PDF is what we want, but we can change this to e.g. jpeg by changing the file extension:

ggsave("figure1.jpg", width=5, height=6)

Specifying width and height is optional, but allows us to perfect the size and aspect ratio for a publication.

Very occasionally you might want to combine multiple plots within the same figure. For this you can use the ggarrange function in the ggpubr package.

More advanced plots

Here is another example:

ggplot(topic_3_solution, aes(x=LactationGroup, y=MilkYield, col=Breed)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  facet_wrap(~ Herd) +
  ylab("Daily milk yield") +
  xlab(NULL) +
  theme_light() +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle = -90, hjust = 0))

This introduces a few more useful things that we have added to the plot:

  • facet_wrap(~ Herd) gives us a different sub-plot for each herd - if needed we can control the layout using nrow and ncol arguments
  • ylab(“Daily milk yield”) changes the y axis label
  • xlab(NULL) removes the x axis label
  • theme_light() changes the overall theme of the plot (removing the grey background etc)
  • theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle = -90, hjust = 0)) makes a specific adjustment to the x axis text (rotating by 90 degrees anti-clockwise, so the text fits better)

We use facet_wrap (and the related facet_grid) quite frequently for generating plots with stratified variables, so that is worth remembering. The ylab and xlab options are also useful, particularly for removing a label where it isn’t needed. I almost always also use theme_light with my plots - if you prefer to have that as the default value then you can use this code at the top of your R script to ensure that every subsequently made plot uses this theme:

theme_set(theme_light())

Getting help

There are a lot of other options to achieve specific things, like theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle = -90, hjust = 0)) in the plot above. We will never be able to remember them all, but searching the internet for the thing you want to achieve may help. For example try to google “ggplot how to rotate axis text” and you will find an answer that can help (just like I did when I wrote this lesson!).

You can also find specific help with ggplot from online books like the R graphics cookbook and the “Data visualisation” chapter of the excellent R for Data Science book. It is a lot of work to get all the way through this book, but it is an extremely useful resource and is kept well updated by the authors (who are also the authors of the tidyverse package).
